: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Schlawe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German: variant of   Schlack  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Schlack","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Heinz.","North German: nickname for a weak or listless person, from Middle Low German <i>slak</i> ‘weak, slack’."]}]},{"name":"vel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Valerie  , and sometimes also of   Valentine ."],"variants":[{"name":"Valerie","meanings":["From the French form of the Latin name <i>Valeria</i>, feminine of <i>Valerius</i>, an old Roman family name apparently derived from <i>valere</i> ‘to be healthy, strong’. The name owes its popularity as a male name in France to the cult of a 3rd-century saint who was converted to Christianity by Martial of Limoges. The masculine form  <b>Valery</b>  is found occasionally in England in the 16th century, but by the 17th century had fallen into disuse."]},{"name":"Valentine","meanings":["form of the Latin name <i>Valentinus</i>, a derivative of <i>valens</i> ‘healthy, strong’. This was the name of a Roman martyr of the 3rd century, whose feast is celebrated on  14 February . This was the date of a pagan fertility festival marking the first stirrings of spring, which has survived in an attenuated form under the patronage of the saint."]}]},{"name":"Eudoxia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of the New Testament Greek names <i>Eudoxia</i> ‘of good appearance’ and <i>Eudokia</i> ‘wellbeing, comfort’. The Byzantine empress  Eudocia  (  d. <i>c</i>.460 ) was the wife of the emperor  Theodosius II . She was a devout Christian, of humble origin, and after the emperor's death in  450  she retired to Jerusalem and spent the last ten years of her life in quiet contemplation."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Audacia vel Eudoxia von Pommern von Schlawe was born about 1188, in Hagen, Neustadt am Rübenberge, Hanover, Lower Saxony, Germany as the daughter of Wratislav von Pommern von Schlawe and Audacia von Schlawe. She married Heinrich “der Schwarze” von Schwerin I about 1200. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1219, at the age of 32."},"et":{"about 1188–1219":"umbes 1188–1219","1188–1219":"1188–1219","1155–1228":"1155–1228","1202–1267":"1202–1267","1204–1287":"1204–1287","1206–Female":"1206–Surnud","1212–1274":"1212–1274","1147–Male":"1147–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","ABT 1202":"umbes 1202","1274":"1274","ABT 1206":"umbes 1206","ABT    1204":"umbes 1204","1206":"1206","1228":"1228","1204":"1204","1147":"1147","1202":"1202","1212":"1212","1267":"1267","1287":"1287","1155":"1155","1188":"1188","about 1200":"umbes 1200","about 1188":"umbes 1188","1219":"1219","Hagen, Neustadt am Rübenberge, Hanover, Lower Saxony, Germany":"Hagen, Neustadt am Rübenberge, Hannover, Niedersachsen, Saksamaa","Wittenberg, Sachsen, Germany":"Landkreis Wittenberg, Provinz Sachsen, Preußen","of,Schwerin,Mecklb-Schwerin,Germany":"Stadt Schwerin, Großherzogtum Mecklenburg-Schwerin"},"fi":{"about 1188–1219":"noin 1188–1219","1188–1219":"1188–1219","1155–1228":"1155–1228","1202–1267":"1202–1267","1204–1287":"1204–1287","1206–Female":"1206–Kuollut","1212–1274":"1212–1274","1147–Male":"1147–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","ABT 1202":"noin 1202","1274":"1274","ABT 1206":"noin 1206","ABT    1204":"noin 1204","1206":"1206","1228":"1228","1204":"1204","1147":"1147","1202":"1202","1212":"1212","1267":"1267","1287":"1287","1155":"1155","1188":"1188","about 1200":"noin 1200","about 1188":"noin 1188","1219":"1219",